1
00:00:00,291 --> 00:00:03,812
Good evening, and welcome to this special meeting of the Medford Zoning Board of Appeals.

2
00:00:04,673 --> 00:00:08,054
We're going to start off by taking a quick roll call, and then we'll get started.

3
00:00:11,275 --> 00:00:11,975
Jim Tirani?

4
00:00:12,575 --> 00:00:12,796
Here.

5
00:00:14,756 --> 00:00:15,556
Yvette Velez?

6
00:00:17,497 --> 00:00:17,857
Present.

7
00:00:19,538 --> 00:00:20,338
Amy Thompson?

8
00:00:21,499 --> 00:00:21,799
Present.

9
00:00:23,199 --> 00:00:23,879
Andre LaRue?

10
00:00:25,060 --> 00:00:25,560
Present.

11
00:00:26,940 --> 00:00:28,241
Mike Caldera, present.

12
00:00:29,200 --> 00:00:30,380
All right, we have a quorum.

13
00:00:30,900 --> 00:00:37,201
Dennis, can you please kick us off?

14
00:00:37,261 --> 00:00:44,683
On March 29, 2023, Governor Haley signed into law a supplemental budget bill, which, among other things, extends the temporary provisions in the Open Meeting Law to March 31, 2025.

15
00:00:45,163 --> 00:00:56,585
Specifically, this further extension allows public bodies to continue holding their meetings remotely without a quorum of the public body physically present at the meeting location and to provide adequate alternative access to remote meetings.

16
00:00:57,452 --> 00:01:05,915
Language does not make any substantive changes to the open meeting laws and extending the expiration date for temporary provisions regarding remote meetings from March 31st, 2023 to March 31st, 2025.

17
00:01:05,955 --> 00:01:10,216
Thank you.

18
00:01:10,316 --> 00:01:14,598
And can you read the first item on the agenda, please?

19
00:01:14,618 --> 00:01:20,180
4000 Mystic Valley Parkway, case number 40B-2022-01, continued from May 15th, 2023.

20
00:01:20,980 --> 00:01:26,542
Presumption of consideration of petition of MVP Mystic LLC, an affiliate of Milwaukee Presidential Trust LLC,

21
00:01:27,075 --> 00:01:39,463
for a comprehensive permit pursuant to Massachusetts General Law's Chapter 40B for multi-family eight-story apartment development consisting of two buildings located in approximately three acres of land at 4000 Mr. Kelly Parkway, property ID 7-02-10.

22
00:01:39,483 --> 00:01:52,592
Proposal will be developed as an approximately 350-unit rental apartment building containing a mix of studio, one, two, and three-bedroom apartments, with 25% of the total units being designated as affordable housing to low and moderate income households.

23
00:01:55,945 --> 00:01:56,145
Great.

24
00:01:56,185 --> 00:01:56,846
Thank you, Dennis.

25
00:01:57,206 --> 00:01:57,867
All right, folks.

26
00:01:59,068 --> 00:02:00,810
So this is a long running hearing.

27
00:02:01,171 --> 00:02:04,074
We've been reviewing this case over the course of many months.

28
00:02:05,535 --> 00:02:12,162
And so at our last hearing, the board first saw an updated plan packet from the applicant.

29
00:02:13,224 --> 00:02:15,947
At that time, there was limited opportunity

30
00:02:17,027 --> 00:02:21,410
for the peer reviewers and the board to review that packet in detail.

31
00:02:21,950 --> 00:02:35,557
And so we requested that our engineering and architectural peer reviewers take some additional time, update their comment letters to reflect the latest changes in the plan packet.

32
00:02:36,098 --> 00:02:43,201
And so one of the primary items we'll be going over today are the two updated peer review letters.

33
00:02:45,240 --> 00:02:49,083
We'll lead off, I'll check in with the applicant, see if there's other updates they'd like to share.

34
00:02:49,463 --> 00:02:51,645
Then we'll go through each of the letters.

35
00:02:52,346 --> 00:02:54,627
This is also the hearing where we intend.

36
00:02:55,905 --> 00:03:12,833
to go through the requested waiver list and have the board make any call outs they have for changes they'd like to see before in a future hearing, we start converging to a list of conditions and a vote.

37
00:03:13,534 --> 00:03:14,614
So that's the plan for today.

38
00:03:14,674 --> 00:03:16,075
We will take public comment.

39
00:03:18,176 --> 00:03:21,638
Yeah, and so with that, I see we have Mr. Alexander for the applicant.

40
00:03:22,706 --> 00:03:25,387
So just wanna check in with you first, Mr. Alexander.

41
00:03:25,407 --> 00:03:32,170
Any updates or comments you'd like to share before we start going into the peer review letters?

42
00:03:33,610 --> 00:03:34,071
Yeah, thank you.

43
00:03:34,091 --> 00:03:35,831
Good evening, Mr. Chair and members of the board.

44
00:03:35,851 --> 00:03:42,454
I think as the agenda, as you laid it out, I think works certainly for us.

45
00:03:43,034 --> 00:03:47,056
In terms of comments, I think, or sort of updates, it might be best if

46
00:03:48,463 --> 00:03:55,467
we hear from the peer reviewers first and then following that but before the waiver discussion we can provide a few updates.

47
00:03:56,287 --> 00:03:57,188
Does that work?

48
00:03:57,448 --> 00:03:58,808
Yeah that works for me.

49
00:03:59,709 --> 00:04:09,754
All right so why don't we start then with Mr. Reardon from Tetra Tech on the engineering comment letter.

50
00:04:11,115 --> 00:04:11,895
Good evening everybody.

51
00:04:13,056 --> 00:04:16,818
Just wanted to let everybody know what we tried to do with our final letter is

52
00:04:17,725 --> 00:04:22,422
in consideration of where we are with the schedule and hoping to close the hearing soon we wanted to sort of.

53
00:04:24,691 --> 00:04:26,833
make sure we tied everything, any loose ends up.

54
00:04:27,153 --> 00:04:36,940
So what we did is any issues that weren't closed out and addressed statically by the applicant, we put a condition in there, because most of the issues were relatively minor.

55
00:04:37,440 --> 00:04:50,329
What we did is we suggested recommended condition language that could defer that to a later point in the design sequence, understanding that this is a preliminary plan, there's still some evolution to the plan that might happen.

56
00:04:51,249 --> 00:05:00,054
when they come around to issuing construction documents for a building permit, they'll have a bit better understanding of their site improvements and some of the other logistical needs of the project.

57
00:05:00,094 --> 00:05:08,999
So what we identified is an opportunity to sort of have a final set of plans that gets, final set of site plans that gets submitted along with the building permit application.

58
00:05:09,799 --> 00:05:13,822
And then as part of that final site plan package, they address any of the outstanding comments.

59
00:05:15,655 --> 00:05:17,937
So in our letter, there's basically three parts.

60
00:05:18,077 --> 00:05:26,566
One is all the old comments, we either indicated that it was addressed or we recommended a condition that could address it in a final set of site plans.

61
00:05:27,567 --> 00:05:31,230
We provided some new comments on what we had seen in the revised submittals.

62
00:05:31,491 --> 00:05:33,072
Most of those are relatively minor.

63
00:05:33,653 --> 00:05:37,557
All of those could be captured on final edits in the final site plans.

64
00:05:38,097 --> 00:05:42,922
And then the last part was just some of our comments relative to their waiver requests.

65
00:05:43,503 --> 00:05:52,973
And I think most of those comments generated were of the type of sort of wanting specificity to the waiver requests.

66
00:05:53,053 --> 00:05:57,758
Just as a case in point, for example, if you waive, for example, the II requirement,

67
00:05:58,886 --> 00:06:03,030
that might have repercussions on the city's MS4 permit requirements.

68
00:06:03,110 --> 00:06:07,995
So the city is required to have an II program and they're required to have new connections do certain things.

69
00:06:08,475 --> 00:06:14,941
So if you inadvertently waive something that wasn't intended to be waived, it could put the city in non-compliance with an existing permit.

70
00:06:15,341 --> 00:06:20,806
So it's kind of important for the applicant to rather than waive a whole requirement or a whole

71
00:06:21,887 --> 00:06:38,300
regulation section to just specifically identify where that relief is needed so that you're not inadvertently either waiving a permit requirement that the town has to comply with, the city has to comply with, or perhaps a critical piece of process that say that the DPW needs or the water department needs.

72
00:06:38,360 --> 00:06:43,664
So just most of those comments related to the waivers were mostly about specificity.

73
00:06:45,305 --> 00:06:47,887
I think we pretty much had seven areas where

74
00:06:49,216 --> 00:06:51,337
sort of some outstanding issues remained.

75
00:06:51,457 --> 00:07:01,462
One was still a little bit murky as to how construction is gonna be managed, the specifics, where a contractor is gonna park, where are they gonna handle material?

76
00:07:01,522 --> 00:07:03,583
How are they gonna handle material storage?

77
00:07:03,603 --> 00:07:08,565
There's not a whole lot of place left on the site to offload trucks or to store material.

78
00:07:08,625 --> 00:07:14,788
So we would expect to have a more developed construction management plan to be submitted as part of the building permit application.

79
00:07:15,209 --> 00:07:17,870
And we're suggesting the board condition as such.

80
00:07:20,220 --> 00:07:26,424
The other thing too is keep in mind there's a notice of intent that's got to go through with the Conservation Commission.

81
00:07:26,484 --> 00:07:34,329
So during that process, the applicant will have to demonstrate a bit better command over how they're going to manage sediment and all that other stuff during construction.

82
00:07:34,369 --> 00:07:39,833
So you've got three things that are going to help you manage it before they actually build the project.

83
00:07:39,973 --> 00:07:42,755
One is the final site plans will have some more detail.

84
00:07:43,307 --> 00:07:53,558
the conservation commission would have chimed in and made sure that they've done enough to control sediment and erosion.

85
00:07:53,998 --> 00:08:01,146
And then hopefully the applicant will have a construction management plan filed with the building permit that'll help you understand how they plan and manage construction.

86
00:08:02,786 --> 00:08:07,927
There's some minor details that are missing that typically we'd see as part of a preliminary plan.

87
00:08:07,987 --> 00:08:13,869
But again, none of those things were huge, but we'd like to see them as part of the final site plans to make sure that they're done correctly.

88
00:08:15,669 --> 00:08:20,351
One of the other issues was a couple of thoughts came to our mind about commercial street.

89
00:08:20,951 --> 00:08:28,673
Right now there's soft cuts proposed around a couple sections where they're planning on extending curb out into the street to create parking islands.

90
00:08:30,573 --> 00:08:53,942
and there's several driveway entrances and probably several feet of damaged curb that's going to have to get fixed so what we're suggesting rather than just sort of have this zigzaggy saw cut around the curb to just simply run a saw cut line right down the edge of parking where they're planning on putting their construction fence so that you have a nice neat paved edge on commercial street and

91
00:08:55,002 --> 00:09:00,064
any miscellaneous damage that might have happened during construction in the area that they were occupying gets fixed as well.

92
00:09:01,185 --> 00:09:08,508
I'm also curious about whether we didn't see on the plans any proposal for lighting on the project side of Commercial Street.

93
00:09:08,528 --> 00:09:11,549
So right now I think there's just three or four lights on the other side.

94
00:09:11,569 --> 00:09:20,033
A little unsure as to how well that's going to do providing light on the project side given how much more

95
00:09:21,090 --> 00:09:28,655
activity and engagement there's gonna be along that edge, that maybe it warrants some additional consideration for lighting along the project side of Commercial Street.

96
00:09:30,257 --> 00:09:31,738
Some final comments on loading.

97
00:09:32,898 --> 00:09:48,890
We suggested that the board put a condition that the applicant define their loading spaces a little bit more clearly in terms of which ones are dedicated for short-term parking, like 15 minutes or less, and which ones are intended for loading where people might be there for a couple hours.

98
00:09:49,510 --> 00:10:03,925
Reason being is you want to make sure that there's always sort of the closer spaces to where the entries are dedicated for the shorter term parking so that delivery drivers and folks like that always have a place to go and they know where they're supposed to go.

99
00:10:05,647 --> 00:10:12,774
Also, just some other minor comments about eliminating a bump out to just provide a little bit more length for the loading area.

100
00:10:14,505 --> 00:10:25,890
And then also to make sure that when they do figure out where the fire panel is going to go, traditionally what happens is the fire department will respond with a large fire truck usually.

101
00:10:25,910 --> 00:10:31,733
It's pretty important to have a place for them to park that's convenient to the fire panel.

102
00:10:32,813 --> 00:10:37,995
Again, all of these things can be handled in the final site plans that we're suggesting get submitted along with the building permit application.

103
00:10:40,688 --> 00:10:44,509
One of the last items was that front drive is still pretty tight.

104
00:10:44,529 --> 00:10:48,431
12 foot aisle with a parallel parking space.

105
00:10:48,651 --> 00:10:56,914
And what's got us a little bit concerned is that there's a very narrow section of sidewalk, which is pinched between the travel lane and the building.

106
00:10:57,034 --> 00:11:05,036
So if you can imagine, if for some reason somebody jumps a curb along that travel lane, the travel lane is already pretty small at 12 feet.

107
00:11:07,332 --> 00:11:15,055
And the curb, there's a curb there, but if someone jumps the curb, someone on the sidewalk has nowhere to go because the building blocks their escape.

108
00:11:15,975 --> 00:11:29,019
So what we're suggesting they do as part of their final site plans, consider whether or not, A, whether they're gonna keep that circulation, and if they are, to consider some sort of protective measure like a bollard or something like that to protect the pedestrians on the sidewalk.

109
00:11:31,960 --> 00:11:33,521
One of the last items was just I.I.

110
00:11:35,675 --> 00:11:37,936
there was a little murky as to what the commitment was.

111
00:11:38,016 --> 00:11:42,018
It sounds like there's just an agreement to do a scope of investigation.

112
00:11:42,038 --> 00:11:46,541
I didn't see anything that indicated exactly what the I.I.

113
00:11:46,581 --> 00:11:47,681
mitigation commitment was.

114
00:11:48,122 --> 00:11:52,664
So what I'd suggest there is that the board be real careful in waiving any part of the I.I.

115
00:11:52,704 --> 00:11:54,285
mitigation requirements because again,

116
00:11:54,960 --> 00:12:00,789
those inflow and infiltration removal requirements are a subject of the town's MS, the city's MS4 permit.

117
00:12:00,829 --> 00:12:06,277
So we don't wanna make sure, we wanna make sure that you're not doing anything that would violate the terms of the town's permit, the city's permit.

118
00:12:07,620 --> 00:12:10,622
And then just the last item was just our waivers.

119
00:12:10,682 --> 00:12:15,506
Again, just make sure that they're real specific in how they request relief.

120
00:12:15,746 --> 00:12:18,207
All of these things are identified explicitly in our letter.

121
00:12:18,328 --> 00:12:22,430
So what we have is we have anywhere where you recommend a condition, it's underlined and italicized.

122
00:12:22,971 --> 00:12:25,913
So if you guys agree with it, you can just cut and paste it, write a new decision.

123
00:12:27,414 --> 00:12:32,879
And there are no, as of this last letter, there are no outstanding items.

124
00:12:32,919 --> 00:12:39,364
So all of the issues have either been addressed by the revised plans or by the condition that we recommend.

125
00:12:41,686 --> 00:12:42,667
Thank you, Mr. Reardon.

126
00:12:44,348 --> 00:12:46,990
What questions do we have from the board for Mr. Reardon?

127
00:12:52,555 --> 00:12:53,536
No, that's not exciting.

128
00:12:58,788 --> 00:12:59,328
Nothing?

129
00:12:59,929 --> 00:13:00,309
I see.

130
00:13:01,129 --> 00:13:04,952
Well, I was holding mine, but I see Mr. Alexander raised his hand.

131
00:13:05,132 --> 00:13:05,872
Please go ahead.

132
00:13:06,252 --> 00:13:07,373
Thank you, Mr. Chair.

133
00:13:07,613 --> 00:13:11,035
I had one question and probably one hopefully clarifying comment.

134
00:13:12,536 --> 00:13:22,182
So the first clarifying comment is, I believe, and we'll double check, but we're not seeking a waiver from the I&I requirement.

135
00:13:23,722 --> 00:13:24,583
I believe in any way.

136
00:13:25,287 --> 00:13:35,893
Um, and so our team, our civil engineering team with, uh, has been in close contact with the city engineer and assistant city and city engineer on scope for INI.

137
00:13:35,993 --> 00:13:38,614
So, um, just want to make, make that comment.

138
00:13:39,495 --> 00:13:43,797
Um, and then, uh, I guess a clarifying question on, on Mr. Reardon, um,

139
00:13:44,918 --> 00:13:49,702
sort of where those final comments and edits would get picked up.

140
00:13:49,922 --> 00:14:04,154
You're mentioning the final site plan, and I just wanted to confirm that that final site plan, I think I heard you say this, but I just wanted to make sure, it's that final set of civil engineering and site plans that's part of the building permit application, is that right?

141
00:14:04,714 --> 00:14:05,155
Correct.

142
00:14:05,515 --> 00:14:06,416
Okay.

143
00:14:06,496 --> 00:14:07,897
So sometimes, Tim, sometimes

144
00:14:09,042 --> 00:14:12,403
on a building permit application, you'll have just a real bare bone site plan.

145
00:14:13,123 --> 00:14:20,965
What we'd like to see is sort of a more refined version of what you currently have addressing the comments that we've got.

146
00:14:21,005 --> 00:14:25,006
We understand completely that this is in the beginning stages of design.

147
00:14:25,026 --> 00:14:30,368
We wanna give you the full opportunity to sort of bet through everything and then get the detail on a set of construction plans.

148
00:14:30,408 --> 00:14:35,829
And then we'll take a look at that when it's issued and then make sure everything is addressed.

149
00:14:38,266 --> 00:14:39,887
Okay, that's great, that makes sense, thanks.

150
00:14:43,628 --> 00:14:45,729
All right, so back to the board.

151
00:14:45,829 --> 00:14:47,050
Questions for Mr. Reardon?

152
00:14:48,711 --> 00:14:49,051
Jamie?

153
00:14:50,652 --> 00:14:52,012
Just one item from the comment.

154
00:14:52,232 --> 00:14:57,595
Can you speak to the item with regards to the transition from the one-way to the two-way?

155
00:14:57,615 --> 00:15:06,739
I know we talked about it last week slightly, but I believe there was a concern about the flow of that one lane into the two lane and the alignment of the lanes.

156
00:15:07,777 --> 00:15:26,110
Right, so they did, they did line them up a little bit better, but there's still a little about a two or three foot offset where the lanes overlap, what we're suggesting is on the final set of site plans, you can address that by doing a, you know, a dashed striped line sometimes you see them at intersections where

157
00:15:26,610 --> 00:15:32,953
you have a dashed line that helps you sort of guide you through your lane and an intersection when there's say two left turns or something like that.

158
00:15:33,453 --> 00:15:49,859
In this situation, what we're suggesting is that they address it with striping because right now that one way lane, if it continued straight, it would occupy about two or three feet of the approaching lane at it.

159
00:15:49,899 --> 00:15:53,721
So it's just, it's slightly off center that they need to address in the final set of site plans.

160
00:15:58,935 --> 00:16:01,416
All right, I'll go next.

161
00:16:01,696 --> 00:16:23,106
So Mr. Reardon, if I understood you correctly, putting aside the waiver list, it sounds like either your comments were resolved or the conditions you've suggested are sufficient to resolve your primary concerns on the engineering and traffic side.

162
00:16:23,126 --> 00:16:23,486
Is that right?

163
00:16:25,203 --> 00:16:35,350
Okay, so then I don't, I certainly we've discussed this at length in other meetings, I don't, I don't want to rehash everything that we've already discussed.

164
00:16:36,030 --> 00:16:39,313
But I guess one clarifying question I have for you.

165
00:16:39,333 --> 00:16:45,817
Of the areas where you're proposing conditions, are there any areas

166
00:16:46,485 --> 00:17:03,270
that you feel could have and perhaps should have been just addressed in the design itself, where the condition is essentially there for the sake of bringing this to a close, but really there was a viable solution that could have been pursued that just wasn't?

167
00:17:05,251 --> 00:17:13,273
No, I think it more falls in the line of, has the project elevated to a point where it can be detailed enough

168
00:17:14,154 --> 00:17:16,798
So I don't think there's anything that I think is wrong.

169
00:17:16,818 --> 00:17:21,244
I think it's just a lot of stuff is still a little bit uncertain or a little bit murky.

170
00:17:21,264 --> 00:17:29,455
The challenge we have in this format is, it's a preliminary plan approval race intended to be sort of a.

171
00:17:30,696 --> 00:17:32,157
constructability exercise.

172
00:17:32,197 --> 00:17:36,040
I think they've definitely addressed the constructability concerns.

173
00:17:36,060 --> 00:17:40,523
They've definitely addressed our gross concerns and our sort of public safety concerns.

174
00:17:42,024 --> 00:17:53,331
Now it's just a matter of just sort of just dotting the Ts and crossing the Is and addressing some, maybe some items that are sort of up to the board's discretion on whether it's important to them.

175
00:17:53,391 --> 00:17:56,313
It's just something that we mentioned as something that might be worth considering.

176
00:17:56,433 --> 00:17:59,035
For example, the lighting along Commercial Street.

177
00:17:59,804 --> 00:18:04,370
And that's certainly not a make or break item, but it's something that we hadn't discussed.

178
00:18:04,430 --> 00:18:07,834
And that I mean, even I hadn't noticed until the very last set of plans.

179
00:18:07,874 --> 00:18:15,003
So I thought it was important to sort of put it on there and you'll give you the opportunity to consider a condition to require it or to not require it.

180
00:18:16,305 --> 00:18:17,006
Okay, thank you.

181
00:18:17,746 --> 00:18:18,848
Other questions from the board?

182
00:18:25,807 --> 00:18:28,308
Mr. Reed and I just have a question.

183
00:18:28,328 --> 00:18:39,833
We've talked a couple of times at points about the safety with storing e-bikes, and I'm wondering if you have any thoughts or recommendations about that.

184
00:18:42,537 --> 00:18:55,464
I think the most appropriate thing is that, and this might fall a little bit into Cliff's purview, but I definitely prefer to see them not stored in the rooms.

185
00:18:55,764 --> 00:18:59,046
And then that sort of heightens our concern about lack of bicycle storage space.

186
00:18:59,086 --> 00:19:08,551
So if you have a prohibition to storing a particular type of bike in your apartment, and there's not enough bike storage space somewhere else.

187
00:19:08,611 --> 00:19:09,432
And I would think that,

188
00:19:10,328 --> 00:19:13,510
storing an electric bike in a room in the garage is relatively safe.

189
00:19:16,752 --> 00:19:32,983
So my concern is that if there's not enough space in the bike storage in the garage, people are less likely to comply with the condition that requires them to keep their e-bike in the bike storage, which means it goes up in their room or in their apartment, and then that's not where you want it.

190
00:19:33,084 --> 00:19:38,007
But aside from that, I don't have any particular concerns about e-bikes in general.

191
00:19:41,154 --> 00:19:41,475
Thank you.

192
00:19:41,875 --> 00:19:58,983
My second question was whether you had any particular thoughts about the intersection with Commercial Street and Mystic Valley Parkway, particularly, I'm talking about what the, really the plaza area that's going to be landscaped.

193
00:19:59,383 --> 00:20:05,006
If there's any recommendations about materials or

194
00:20:08,743 --> 00:20:11,346
